{"title_page": "South Island robin", "text_new": "{{short description|Passerine species of bird native to New Zealand's South Island}}\n{{EngvarB|date=November 2017}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2017}}\n{{speciesbox\n| name = South Island robin\n| status = LC\n| status_system = IUCN3.1\n| status_ref =<ref name=IUCN>BirdLife International 2016. Petroica australis. The IUCN Red List of Threatened Species 2016: e.T103734942A93987322. https://doi.org/10.2305/IUCN.UK.2016-3.RLTS.T103734942A93987322.en. Downloaded on 19 August 2019.</ref>\n| image = 070308 Stewart Island robin on Ulva.jpg\n| genus = Petroica\n| species = australis\n| authority = [[Anders Sparrman|Sparrman]], 1788\n}}\n\nThe '''South Island robin''' (''Petroica australis''), is a [[house sparrow|sparrow]]-sized bird found only in [[New Zealand]], where it has the status of a protected endemic species. The birds are sparsely distributed through the [[South Island, New Zealand|South Island]] and [[Stewart Island/Rakiura]], although the distribution is not continuous. The nominate, and the Stewart Island robin (''P. australis rakiura'') are the two [[subspecies]]. The species is closely related to the [[North Island robin]] (formerly ''P. australis longipes'', now considered a distinct species),<ref name=Miller>{{cite journal|last1=Miller|first1=Hilary C.|last2=Lambert|first2=David M.|year=2006|title=A molecular phylogeny of New Zealand's Petroica (Aves: Petroicidae) species based on mitochondrial DNA sequences|journal=Molecular Phylogenetics and Evolution|volume=40|issue=3|pages=844\u2013855|doi=10.1016/j.ympev.2006.04.012|pmid=16750641}}</ref> and also to the extremely rare [[black robin]] (''P. traversi'') of the [[Chatham Islands]].\n\n==Description==\n\nThe South Island robin is a small passerine, 10\u201318&nbsp;cm in length and weighing around 35 g. North Island robins do resemble both females and juveniles of the South Island robins, as well as all the Stewart Island robins, which can sometimes make it difficult to distinguish between the three. The females and juveniles within a particular group of robins look similar to each other, although newly independent juveniles may not yet have the more lightly coloured breast patch.<ref name=PowleslandA>{{cite book|last=Powlesland|first=R. G.|year=1997|title=Protocols for monitoring New Zealand robins: Petroica australis|series=Department of Conservation Technical Series|volume=13|publisher=New Zealand Department of Conservation}}</ref> However, male North Island robins are almost black with a white spot just above the beak, as well as the greyish-white lower breast. Females and juveniles are greyer with more variable pale patches on their breasts and throats. Male South Island robins are dark grey, except for the distinct yellowish-white lower chest, while females and juveniles are again lighter grey with a less distinct breast. Finally, Stewart Island robins look similar to North Island robins (both males and females).<ref name=IUCN/>\n\nNew Zealand robins are relatively long-lived; life-spans of at least 14 years have been recorded in the wild.\n\n==Taxonomy==\n[[File:New Zealand Robin.jpg|thumb|left|South Island robin]]\nThe South Island robin has two subspecies: ''P. australis australis'', the nominate form, and ''P. australis rakiura'', the Stewart Island robin. These subspecies do not overlap in their distributions. The [[North Island robin]] (''P. longipes''), the [[tomtit]] (''Petroica macrocephala''), and the [[black robin]] (''Petroica traversi'') in the Chatham Islands are closely related species. ''P. traversi'' seems to be a Chatham Island derivative of ''P. australis'', although the position of the most recent common ancestor has yet to be determined.<ref name=Miller/> The family [[Petroicidae]] of Australasian robins has a total of 49 species, mostly in Australia, [[New Zealand]], and [[New Guinea]].<ref name=Gill>Gill, F. and D. Donsker, eds. (2020). IOC World Bird List (v 10.1). Doi 10.14344/IOC.ML.10.1.  http://www.worldbirdnames.org/</ref>.\n\n==Fossil record==\nThere is molecular phylogenetic evidence to suggest two waves of immigration by the Petroica genus from Australia. ''P. longipes'' and ''P. australis'' can be traced to the first and ''P. macrocephala'' to the second wave. The evidence suggests that ''P. longipes'' and ''P. australis'' began to diverge prior to the [[Pleistocene]] era, and that the two South Island subspecies of ''P. australis'' began to diverge after the [[Pleistocene]] era. The separation time for the former was about three million years, and only 10,000 years (i.e., postglacial) for the latter. Fossils of New Zealand robins can sometimes be found near pit fall deposits, as they do most of their feeding/foraging on the ground.<ref name=\"ref5\">{{cite book|last1=Worthy|first1=Trevor H.|last2=Holdaway|first2=Richard N.|year=2002|chapter=Shorebirds, Parrots and Passerines|title=The Lost World of the Moa|pages=410\u2013440}}</ref> The fossil record also indicates the robins' presence throughout lowland New Zealand until drastic habitat reduction through deforestation by the [[Polynesians|Polynesian]] ancestors of the [[M\u0101ori people|M\u0101ori]] and later European colonisers.<ref name=\"ref6\">{{cite journal|last=Borkin|first=K. M.|last2=Goodman|first2=A. J.|last3=Mayhew|first3=K.|last4=Smith|first4=E.|year=2007|title=South Island robin (Petroica australis australis) abundance and leaf-litter invertebrates in plantation and native forest|journal=Notornis|volume=54|issue=2|pages=65}}</ref>\n\n==Distribution==\n[[File:Petroica australis -Southland District, South Island, New Zealand-8.jpg|thumb|right|South Island robin, [[Southland District]]]]\nHistorically, the South Island robin inhabited much of the lowland of New Zealand's South Island, but its distribution has become much more patchy in the last century due to habitat loss and introduced predation.<ref name=\"ref6\"/>  There are two populations on the east coast of the South Island, and they are slightly more common in the north and west.<ref name=IUCN/> It has fared slightly better than the Stewart Island robin, which has been relegated to 3 subpopulations, all of which are in [[Leptospermum]] swamp scrubland\u2014although this is not their preferred habitat, it is less heavily populated by mammalian predators. Total population was lower than 500 individuals at one point.<ref name=\"ref7\">{{cite journal|last1=Laws|first1=R. J.|last2=Jamieson|first2=I. G.|year=2011|title=Is lack of evidence of inbreeding depression in a threatened New Zealand robin indicative of reduced genetic load?|journal=Animal Conservation|volume=14|issue=1|pages=47\u201355|doi=10.1111/j.1469-1795.2010.00388.x}}</ref> A programme of translocation to predator-free islands (such as [[Ulva Island (New Zealand)|Ulva Island]], Motuara Island, and Nukuwaiata Island) has since been instituted that has been relatively successful at establishing new populations (around 600 individuals on Motuara alone).<ref name=Hale>{{cite journal|last1=Hale|first1=K. A.|last2=Briskie|first2=J. V.|year=2007|title=Decreased immunocompetence in a severely bottlenecked population of an endemic New Zealand bird.|journal=Animal Conservation|volume=10|issue=1|pages=2\u201310|doi=10.1111/j.1469-1795.2006.00059.x}}</ref> In the South Island, ''P. australis'' has a strong affinity for [[Douglas fir]] plantations rather than native forests ([[Kunzea ericoides|kanuka]] trees) or [[Monterey pine]] plantations, apparently due to forest structure rather than strict food availability or viable nesting sites, as the species prefers structurally simple forests with dense, even canopies, and ground covered with leaf litter.<ref name=\"ref6\"/> When the population was introduced to Ulva Island, nesting was positively correlated with presence of broad-leaved coastal vegetation.<ref name=\"ref10\">{{cite journal|last1=Steffens|first1=K. E.|last2=Seddon|first2=P. J.|last3=Mathieu|first3=R.|last4=Jamieson|first4=I. G.|year=2005|title=Habitat selection by South Island saddlebacks and Stewart Island robins reintroduced to Ulva Island|journal=New Zealand Journal of Ecology|volume=2005|pages=221\u2013229}}</ref>\n\n==Behaviour and ecology==\n\n===Breeding===\n\nSouth Island robins are [[Monogamy|genetically monogamous]], and extra-pair paternity is rare. As they do typically remain monogamous, are non-migratory, and remain on their breeding territories year-round, a male and female in one territory will compete for food resources during non-breeding times. Competition is reduced somewhat by slightly different foraging methods; however, they will steal from their mate's cache if given the opportunity.<ref name=Powlesland/> Males do dominate females, and thus will aggressively exclude females from food, such that females will only access food sources when unattended by the males.<ref name=SteerBurns>{{cite journal|last1=Steer|first1=Jamie|last2=Burns|first2=KC|year=2008|title=Seasonal variation in male-female competition, cooperation and selfish hoarding in a monogamous songbird|journal=Behavioral Ecology and Sociobiology|volume=62|issue=7|pages=1175\u20131183|doi=10.1007/s00265-008-0546-z}}</ref> During breeding season, the female is solely responsible for nest building and incubation, and the male will provide the female and the hatchlings with food.<ref name=PowleslandA/>\n\nSouth Island robins become sexually mature between six and 12 months of age. They begin their breeding season fairly early in August or September (Southern Hemisphere spring) and thus can make use of the winter's remaining food stores during this time.<ref name=Powlesland/> They build open-cup nests in tree-forks or inside tree cavities. Incubation lasts 18 days, and chicks leave the nest after 21 days. Five to 25 days after fledglings leave the nest, the pair may breed again. Modal clutch size is two eggs,<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Taylor|first1=S. S.|last2=Jamieson|first2=I. G.|last3=Wallis|first3=G. P.|year=2007|title=Historic and contemporary levels of genetic variation in two New Zealand passerines with different histories of decline|journal=Journal of Evolutionary Biology|volume=20|issue=5|pages=2035\u20132047|doi=10.1111/j.1420-9101.2007.01362.x|pmid=17714320}}</ref> with the expected inverse correlation between size and number of eggs.<ref name=PowleslandBolton>{{cite journal|last1=Boulton|first1=Rebecca L|last2=Powlesland|first2=Ralph G.|year=2008|title=Variation in egg size and nest survival with female age in the South Island Robin Petroica australis|journal=Ibis|volume=150|issue=4|pages=824\u2013828|doi=10.1111/j.1474-919x.2008.00853.x}}</ref> Replacement clutches in the case of loss of eggs or nestlings to predation can be produced relatively rapidly, within 3\u201310 days.<ref name=PowleslandA/>\n\n===Feeding===\n[[File:NZ Robin 2008.JPG|thumb|right|Stewart Island robin]]\nInvertebrates, including earthworms, beetles, and other arthropods foraged from the leaf litter comprise most of the South Island robins' diet.<ref name=\"ref5\"/> Invertebrate prey may be [[Hoarding (animal behavior)|cached]] whole or in portions. Single items are cached at separate sites. Prey is typically stored within 10 metres of where it was procured, even if the bird is outside its own territory. In the winter the primary cache is earthworms, while during the summer the trend is toward cicadas. South Island robins have a very good memory of their storage sites; a male was observed to empty as many as five consecutive caches before returning the stores to his mate during incubation.<ref name=Powlesland>{{cite journal|last=Powlesland|first=R. G.|year=1980|title=Food-Storing Behavior of the South Island Robin|journal=Mauri Ora|volume=8|pages=11}}</ref> The birds have demonstrated an ability to differentiate and prioritise caches of varying sizes, up to 12 total items, without any training, which appears to be the highest recorded numerical competency of any wild animal.<ref name=HuntBurns>{{cite journal|last1=Hunt|first1=Simon|last2=Low|first2=Jason|last3=Burns|first3=K.C.|year=2008|title=Adaptive numerical competency in a food-hoarding songbird|journal=Proceedings of the Royal Society of London B: Biological Sciences|volume=275|issue=1649|pages=2373\u20132379|doi=10.1098/rspb.2008.0702|pmc=2603231|pmid=18611847}}</ref> Because of its high metabolic rate, a robin might spend as much as 90% of its day foraging or storing during the winter.<ref name=Powlesland/> South Island robins have also been observed to eat berries on occasion, however these are not cached.<ref name=\"ref5\"/>\n\n===Vocalisation===\n[[File:Southislandrobin.jpg|thumb|right|South Island robin]]\nA male's call during non-breeding season is a series of loud notes with descending frequency which start in rapid succession and finish slowly. During breeding season, the males resort to full song to court the females. Full song is a loud, clear, and continuous song which can last for more than 30 minutes with very brief pauses, and is typically sung from the canopy or an [[Rainforest#Emergent layer|emergent]] tree.<ref name=PowleslandA/> Singing also appears to be performed as part of a strategic regulation of body mass. While robins sing during the [[Dawn chorus (birds)|dawn chorus]] as well as throughout the day, they seem to increase their singing according to food availability. When they have had more food, they will increase energetic behaviours such as singing to arrive at a strategic mass by dusk. Thus, even though two robins might begin the day with different weights, they will end the day with similar weights. A side effect of this behaviour might be the showcasing of a particular male's ability to sequester resources: the longer he sings, the more capable he is of finding food, and thus a better candidate for a mate.<ref name=Barnett>{{cite journal|last1=Barnett|first1=Craig A.|last2=Briskie|first2=James V.|year=2011|title=Strategic Regulation of Body Mass and Singing Behavior in New Zealand Robins|journal=Ethology|volume=117|issue=1|pages=28\u201336|doi=10.1111/j.1439-0310.2010.01844.x}}</ref>\n\n==Conservation==\n\nThe South Island robin is listed as being of [[least concern]] on the [[IUCN Red List]].<ref name=IUCN/> However, the Stewart Island robin (''Petroica australis rakiura'') has gone through a couple of bottlenecked populations recently because of deforestation and habitat loss, as well as introduced predators, such as rats, stoats, and feral cats.<ref name=Hale></ref> Because of this sharp decline in the Stewart Island population, several attempts have been made to translocate the Stewart Island robin to other islands nearby where introduced predators do not exist or have been eradicated (see [[South Island robin#Distribution|above]]. However, many of these translocations have involved 12 or fewer colonising individuals, making inbreeding nearly unavoidable. This has led to some apparent immunocompetency issues as well as reproduction problems. On Motuara Island high rates of hatching failure as well as fewer clutches were observed.<ref name=Hale/> Inbreeding and its genetic and immunological consequences therefore remain a concern with this subspecies.\n\nIn contrast, birds in the South Island do not show much genetic loss in comparison with historical populations, although their distribution on the island has become increasingly fragmented.<ref name=Taylor>{{cite journal|last1=Taylor|first1=S. S.|last2=Boessenkool|first2=S.|last3=Jamieson|first3=I. G.|year=2008|title=Genetic monogamy in two long\u2010lived New Zealand passerines|journal=Journal of Avian Biology|volume=39|issue=5|pages=579\u2013583|doi=10.1111/j.0908-8857.2008.04331.x}}</ref>\n\n==South Island robins and 1080 poison==\n\nA number of robin deaths have been recorded as a result of accidental [[sodium fluoroacetate|1080]] poisoning following pest control operations.<ref name=spurr>{{cite book|last=Spurr|first=E.|year=2000|chapter=Impacts of possum control on non-target species|editor=T.L. Montague|title=The brushtail possum: biology, impact and management of an introduced marsupial|publisher=Manaaki Whenua Press|location=Lincoln}}</ref> Most of these were associated with four specific operations in the 1980s that used poor-quality carrot baits.<ref name=\"pce\">{{cite web|url=http://www.pce.parliament.nz/publications/all-publications/evaluating-the-use-of-1080-predators-poisons-and-silent-forests/|title=Evaluating the use of 1080: Predators, poisons and silent forests|date=June 2011|publisher=Parliamentary Commissioner for the Environment|accessdate=7 June 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110614233345/http://www.pce.parliament.nz/publications/all-publications/evaluating-the-use-of-1080-predators-poisons-and-silent-forests|archivedate=14 June 2011|df=dmy-all}}</ref> These instances aside, robins have generally responded well to pest control programmes using aerial 1080 operations, with increased chick and adult survival, and increases in population size.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Powlesland|first1=R. G.|last2=Knegtmans|first2=J. W.|last3=Marshall|first3=I. S. J.|year=1999|title=Costs and benefits of aerial 1080 possum control operations using carrot baits to North Island robins (Petroica australis longipes), Pureora Forest Park|journal=New Zealand Journal of Ecology|volume=1999|pages=149\u2013159|url=http://www.lincoln.ac.nz/PageFiles/7074/3474_Powleslandetal__s10663.pdf}}</ref> A 2012 scientific study of a [[Bird ringing|marked]] population by the [[University of Otago]] during a contemporary 1080 poison operation using cereal baits showed no negative impact on robins and suggested a likely population increase by reducing predation pressure from introduced mammals.<ref name=\"TVNZ One News\">{{cite news |url=http://tvnz.co.nz/national-news/study-finds-1080-has-positive-effect-bird-population-video-4844337 |title=Study finds 1080 has positive effect on bird population |author=TVNZ |date=22 April 2012 |work=[[TVNZ]] |accessdate=26 April 2012}}</ref><!-- DEAD LINK Schadewinkel et al. |title=The effect of aerial application of 1080 cereal baits for possum control on South Island robin (Petroica australis) in the Silver Peaks, Dunedin'|url=http://tbfree.org.nz/Portals/0/Research/1080%20-%20robin%20report_final-revised.pdf -->\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.doc.govt.nz/conservation/native-animals/birds/land-birds/nz-robin-toutouwai/ New Zealand Robin] on [[Department of Conservation (New Zealand)|Department of Conservation]] website\n* [http://www.nzbirds.com/birds/toutouwai.html Factsheet on toutouwai, the New Zealand robin] at NZBirds.com\n* [http://www.teara.govt.nz/en/1966/robin/1/ Information about New Zealand robins] on [[Te Ara: The Encyclopedia of New Zealand|Te Ara]]\n* [http://www.doc.org.nz/upload/documents/science-and-technical/docts13.pdf Protocols for monitoring New Zealand robins(Petroica australis)] - [[Department of Conservation (New Zealand)|Department of Conservation]] Technical Series No. 13\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=bwLBfaX4VjE/ Video footage of New Zealand robins] on the [[Animal Health Board (New Zealand)|Animal Health Board]] YouTube Channel\n\n{{Petroicidae}}\n{{Birds of New Zealand}}\n{{Portal bar|Birds|New Zealand}}\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q1051396}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:robin, South Island}}\n[[Category:Petroica|South Island robin]]\n[[Category:Birds of the South Island]]\n[[Category:Endemic fauna of New Zealand]]\n[[Category:Birds described in 1788|South Island robin]]\n[[Category:Taxa named by Anders Sparrman]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Passerine species of bird native to New Zealand's South Island}}\n{{EngvarB|date=November 2017}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2017}}\n{{speciesbox\n| name = South Island robin\n| status = LC\n| status_system = IUCN3.1\n| status_ref =<ref name=IUCN>BirdLife International 2016. Petroica australis. The IUCN Red List of Threatened Species 2016: e.T103734942A93987322. https://doi.org/10.2305/IUCN.UK.2016-3.RLTS.T103734942A93987322.en. Downloaded on 19 August 2019.</ref>\n| image = 070308 Stewart Island robin on Ulva.jpg\n| genus = Petroica\n| species = australis\n| authority = [[Anders Sparrman|Sparrman]], 1788\n}}\n\nThe '''South Island robin''' (''Petroica australis''), is a [[house sparrow|sparrow]]-sized bird found only in [[New Zealand]], where it has the status of a protected endemic species. The birds are sparsely distributed through the [[South Island, New Zealand|South Island]] and [[Stewart Island/Rakiura]], although the distribution is not continuous. The nominate, and the Stewart Island robin (''P. australis rakiura'') are the two [[subspecies]]. The species is closely related to the [[North Island robin]] (formerly ''P. australis longipes'', now considered a distinct species),<ref name=Miller>{{cite journal|last1=Miller|first1=Hilary C.|last2=Lambert|first2=David M.|year=2006|title=A molecular phylogeny of New Zealand's Petroica (Aves: Petroicidae) species based on mitochondrial DNA sequences|journal=Molecular Phylogenetics and Evolution|volume=40|issue=3|pages=844\u2013855|doi=10.1016/j.ympev.2006.04.012|pmid=16750641}}</ref> and also to the extremely rare [[black robin]] (''P. traversi'') of the [[Chatham Islands]].\n\n==Description==\n\nThe South Island robin is a small passerine, 10\u201318&nbsp;cm in length and weighing around 35 g. North Island robins do resemble both females and juveniles of the South Island robins, as well as all the Stewart Island robins, which can sometimes make it difficult to distinguish between the three. The females and juveniles within a particular group of robins look similar to each other, although newly independent juveniles may not yet have the more lightly coloured breast patch.<ref name=PowleslandA>{{cite book|last=Powlesland|first=R. G.|year=1997|title=Protocols for monitoring New Zealand robins: Petroica australis|series=Department of Conservation Technical Series|volume=13|publisher=New Zealand Department of Conservation}}</ref> However, male North Island robins are almost black with a white spot just above the beak, as well as the greyish-white lower breast. Females and juveniles are greyer with more variable pale patches on their breasts and throats. Male South Island robins are dark grey, except for the distinct yellowish-white lower chest, while females and juveniles are again lighter grey with a less distinct breast. Finally, Stewart Island robins look similar to North Island robins (both males and females).<ref name=IUCN/>\n\nNew Zealand robins are relatively long-lived; life-spans of at least 14 years have been recorded in the wild.\n\n==Taxonomy==\n[[File:New Zealand Robin.jpg|thumb|left|South Island robin]]\nThe South Island robin has two subspecies: ''P. australis australis'', the nominate form, and ''P. australis rakiura'', the Stewart Island robin. These subspecies do not overlap in their distributions. The [[North Island robin]] (''P. longipes''), the [[tomtit]] (''Petroica macrocephala''), and the [[black robin]] (''Petroica traversi'') in the Chatham Islands are closely related species. ''P. traversi'' seems to be a Chatham Island derivative of ''P. australis'', although the position of the most recent common ancestor has yet to be determined.<ref name=Miller/> The family [[Petroicidae]] of Australasian robins has a total of 49 species, mostly in Australia, [[New Zealand]], and [[New Guinea]].<ref>Gill, F. and D. Donsker, eds. (2020). IOC World Bird List (v 10.1). Doi 10.14344/IOC.ML.10.1.  http://www.worldbirdnames.org/</ref>.\n\n==Fossil record==\nThere is molecular phylogenetic evidence to suggest two waves of immigration by the Petroica genus from Australia. ''P. longipes'' and ''P. australis'' can be traced to the first and ''P. macrocephala'' to the second wave. The evidence suggests that ''P. longipes'' and ''P. australis'' began to diverge prior to the [[Pleistocene]] era, and that the two South Island subspecies of ''P. australis'' began to diverge after the [[Pleistocene]] era. The separation time for the former was about three million years, and only 10,000 years (i.e., postglacial) for the latter. Fossils of New Zealand robins can sometimes be found near pit fall deposits, as they do most of their feeding/foraging on the ground.<ref name=\"ref5\">{{cite book|last1=Worthy|first1=Trevor H.|last2=Holdaway|first2=Richard N.|year=2002|chapter=Shorebirds, Parrots and Passerines|title=The Lost World of the Moa|pages=410\u2013440}}</ref> The fossil record also indicates the robins' presence throughout lowland New Zealand until drastic habitat reduction through deforestation by the [[Polynesians|Polynesian]] ancestors of the [[M\u0101ori people|M\u0101ori]] and later European colonisers.<ref name=\"ref6\">{{cite journal|last=Borkin|first=K. M.|last2=Goodman|first2=A. J.|last3=Mayhew|first3=K.|last4=Smith|first4=E.|year=2007|title=South Island robin (Petroica australis australis) abundance and leaf-litter invertebrates in plantation and native forest|journal=Notornis|volume=54|issue=2|pages=65}}</ref>\n\n==Distribution==\n[[File:Petroica australis -Southland District, South Island, New Zealand-8.jpg|thumb|right|South Island robin, [[Southland District]]]]\nHistorically, the South Island robin inhabited much of the lowland of New Zealand's South Island, but its distribution has become much more patchy in the last century due to habitat loss and introduced predation.<ref name=\"ref6\"/>  There are two populations on the east coast of the South Island, and they are slightly more common in the north and west.<ref name=IUCN/> It has fared slightly better than the Stewart Island robin, which has been relegated to 3 subpopulations, all of which are in [[Leptospermum]] swamp scrubland\u2014although this is not their preferred habitat, it is less heavily populated by mammalian predators. Total population was lower than 500 individuals at one point.<ref name=\"ref7\">{{cite journal|last1=Laws|first1=R. J.|last2=Jamieson|first2=I. G.|year=2011|title=Is lack of evidence of inbreeding depression in a threatened New Zealand robin indicative of reduced genetic load?|journal=Animal Conservation|volume=14|issue=1|pages=47\u201355|doi=10.1111/j.1469-1795.2010.00388.x}}</ref> A programme of translocation to predator-free islands (such as [[Ulva Island (New Zealand)|Ulva Island]], Motuara Island, and Nukuwaiata Island) has since been instituted that has been relatively successful at establishing new populations (around 600 individuals on Motuara alone).<ref name=Hale>{{cite journal|last1=Hale|first1=K. A.|last2=Briskie|first2=J. V.|year=2007|title=Decreased immunocompetence in a severely bottlenecked population of an endemic New Zealand bird.|journal=Animal Conservation|volume=10|issue=1|pages=2\u201310|doi=10.1111/j.1469-1795.2006.00059.x}}</ref> In the South Island, ''P. australis'' has a strong affinity for [[Douglas fir]] plantations rather than native forests ([[Kunzea ericoides|kanuka]] trees) or [[Monterey pine]] plantations, apparently due to forest structure rather than strict food availability or viable nesting sites, as the species prefers structurally simple forests with dense, even canopies, and ground covered with leaf litter.<ref name=\"ref6\"/> When the population was introduced to Ulva Island, nesting was positively correlated with presence of broad-leaved coastal vegetation.<ref name=\"ref10\">{{cite journal|last1=Steffens|first1=K. E.|last2=Seddon|first2=P. J.|last3=Mathieu|first3=R.|last4=Jamieson|first4=I. G.|year=2005|title=Habitat selection by South Island saddlebacks and Stewart Island robins reintroduced to Ulva Island|journal=New Zealand Journal of Ecology|volume=2005|pages=221\u2013229}}</ref>\n\n==Behaviour and ecology==\n\n===Breeding===\n\nSouth Island robins are [[Monogamy|genetically monogamous]], and extra-pair paternity is rare. As they do typically remain monogamous, are non-migratory, and remain on their breeding territories year-round, a male and female in one territory will compete for food resources during non-breeding times. Competition is reduced somewhat by slightly different foraging methods; however, they will steal from their mate's cache if given the opportunity.<ref name=Powlesland/> Males do dominate females, and thus will aggressively exclude females from food, such that females will only access food sources when unattended by the males.<ref name=SteerBurns>{{cite journal|last1=Steer|first1=Jamie|last2=Burns|first2=KC|year=2008|title=Seasonal variation in male-female competition, cooperation and selfish hoarding in a monogamous songbird|journal=Behavioral Ecology and Sociobiology|volume=62|issue=7|pages=1175\u20131183|doi=10.1007/s00265-008-0546-z}}</ref> During breeding season, the female is solely responsible for nest building and incubation, and the male will provide the female and the hatchlings with food.<ref name=PowleslandA/>\n\nSouth Island robins become sexually mature between six and 12 months of age. They begin their breeding season fairly early in August or September (Southern Hemisphere spring) and thus can make use of the winter's remaining food stores during this time.<ref name=Powlesland/> They build open-cup nests in tree-forks or inside tree cavities. Incubation lasts 18 days, and chicks leave the nest after 21 days. Five to 25 days after fledglings leave the nest, the pair may breed again. Modal clutch size is two eggs,<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Taylor|first1=S. S.|last2=Jamieson|first2=I. G.|last3=Wallis|first3=G. P.|year=2007|title=Historic and contemporary levels of genetic variation in two New Zealand passerines with different histories of decline|journal=Journal of Evolutionary Biology|volume=20|issue=5|pages=2035\u20132047|doi=10.1111/j.1420-9101.2007.01362.x|pmid=17714320}}</ref> with the expected inverse correlation between size and number of eggs.<ref name=PowleslandBolton>{{cite journal|last1=Boulton|first1=Rebecca L|last2=Powlesland|first2=Ralph G.|year=2008|title=Variation in egg size and nest survival with female age in the South Island Robin Petroica australis|journal=Ibis|volume=150|issue=4|pages=824\u2013828|doi=10.1111/j.1474-919x.2008.00853.x}}</ref> Replacement clutches in the case of loss of eggs or nestlings to predation can be produced relatively rapidly, within 3\u201310 days.<ref name=PowleslandA/>\n\n===Feeding===\n[[File:NZ Robin 2008.JPG|thumb|right|Stewart Island robin]]\nInvertebrates, including earthworms, beetles, and other arthropods foraged from the leaf litter comprise most of the South Island robins' diet.<ref name=\"ref5\"/> Invertebrate prey may be [[Hoarding (animal behavior)|cached]] whole or in portions. Single items are cached at separate sites. Prey is typically stored within 10 metres of where it was procured, even if the bird is outside its own territory. In the winter the primary cache is earthworms, while during the summer the trend is toward cicadas. South Island robins have a very good memory of their storage sites; a male was observed to empty as many as five consecutive caches before returning the stores to his mate during incubation.<ref name=Powlesland>{{cite journal|last=Powlesland|first=R. G.|year=1980|title=Food-Storing Behavior of the South Island Robin|journal=Mauri Ora|volume=8|pages=11}}</ref> The birds have demonstrated an ability to differentiate and prioritise caches of varying sizes, up to 12 total items, without any training, which appears to be the highest recorded numerical competency of any wild animal.<ref name=HuntBurns>{{cite journal|last1=Hunt|first1=Simon|last2=Low|first2=Jason|last3=Burns|first3=K.C.|year=2008|title=Adaptive numerical competency in a food-hoarding songbird|journal=Proceedings of the Royal Society of London B: Biological Sciences|volume=275|issue=1649|pages=2373\u20132379|doi=10.1098/rspb.2008.0702|pmc=2603231|pmid=18611847}}</ref> Because of its high metabolic rate, a robin might spend as much as 90% of its day foraging or storing during the winter.<ref name=Powlesland/> South Island robins have also been observed to eat berries on occasion, however these are not cached.<ref name=\"ref5\"/>\n\n===Vocalisation===\n[[File:Southislandrobin.jpg|thumb|right|South Island robin]]\nA male's call during non-breeding season is a series of loud notes with descending frequency which start in rapid succession and finish slowly. During breeding season, the males resort to full song to court the females. Full song is a loud, clear, and continuous song which can last for more than 30 minutes with very brief pauses, and is typically sung from the canopy or an [[Rainforest#Emergent layer|emergent]] tree.<ref name=PowleslandA/> Singing also appears to be performed as part of a strategic regulation of body mass. While robins sing during the [[Dawn chorus (birds)|dawn chorus]] as well as throughout the day, they seem to increase their singing according to food availability. When they have had more food, they will increase energetic behaviours such as singing to arrive at a strategic mass by dusk. Thus, even though two robins might begin the day with different weights, they will end the day with similar weights. A side effect of this behaviour might be the showcasing of a particular male's ability to sequester resources: the longer he sings, the more capable he is of finding food, and thus a better candidate for a mate.<ref name=Barnett>{{cite journal|last1=Barnett|first1=Craig A.|last2=Briskie|first2=James V.|year=2011|title=Strategic Regulation of Body Mass and Singing Behavior in New Zealand Robins|journal=Ethology|volume=117|issue=1|pages=28\u201336|doi=10.1111/j.1439-0310.2010.01844.x}}</ref>\n\n==Conservation==\n\nThe South Island robin is listed as being of [[least concern]] on the [[IUCN Red List]].<ref name=IUCN/> However, the Stewart Island robin (''Petroica australis rakiura'') has gone through a couple of bottlenecked populations recently because of deforestation and habitat loss, as well as introduced predators, such as rats, stoats, and feral cats.<ref name=Hale></ref> Because of this sharp decline in the Stewart Island population, several attempts have been made to translocate the Stewart Island robin to other islands nearby where introduced predators do not exist or have been eradicated (see [[South Island robin#Distribution|above]]. However, many of these translocations have involved 12 or fewer colonising individuals, making inbreeding nearly unavoidable. This has led to some apparent immunocompetency issues as well as reproduction problems. On Motuara Island high rates of hatching failure as well as fewer clutches were observed.<ref name=Hale/> Inbreeding and its genetic and immunological consequences therefore remain a concern with this subspecies.\n\nIn contrast, birds in the South Island do not show much genetic loss in comparison with historical populations, although their distribution on the island has become increasingly fragmented.<ref name=Taylor>{{cite journal|last1=Taylor|first1=S. S.|last2=Boessenkool|first2=S.|last3=Jamieson|first3=I. G.|year=2008|title=Genetic monogamy in two long\u2010lived New Zealand passerines|journal=Journal of Avian Biology|volume=39|issue=5|pages=579\u2013583|doi=10.1111/j.0908-8857.2008.04331.x}}</ref>\n\n==South Island robins and 1080 poison==\n\nA number of robin deaths have been recorded as a result of accidental [[sodium fluoroacetate|1080]] poisoning following pest control operations.<ref name=spurr>{{cite book|last=Spurr|first=E.|year=2000|chapter=Impacts of possum control on non-target species|editor=T.L. Montague|title=The brushtail possum: biology, impact and management of an introduced marsupial|publisher=Manaaki Whenua Press|location=Lincoln}}</ref> Most of these were associated with four specific operations in the 1980s that used poor-quality carrot baits.<ref name=\"pce\">{{cite web|url=http://www.pce.parliament.nz/publications/all-publications/evaluating-the-use-of-1080-predators-poisons-and-silent-forests/|title=Evaluating the use of 1080: Predators, poisons and silent forests|date=June 2011|publisher=Parliamentary Commissioner for the Environment|accessdate=7 June 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110614233345/http://www.pce.parliament.nz/publications/all-publications/evaluating-the-use-of-1080-predators-poisons-and-silent-forests|archivedate=14 June 2011|df=dmy-all}}</ref> These instances aside, robins have generally responded well to pest control programmes using aerial 1080 operations, with increased chick and adult survival, and increases in population size.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Powlesland|first1=R. G.|last2=Knegtmans|first2=J. W.|last3=Marshall|first3=I. S. J.|year=1999|title=Costs and benefits of aerial 1080 possum control operations using carrot baits to North Island robins (Petroica australis longipes), Pureora Forest Park|journal=New Zealand Journal of Ecology|volume=1999|pages=149\u2013159|url=http://www.lincoln.ac.nz/PageFiles/7074/3474_Powleslandetal__s10663.pdf}}</ref> A 2012 scientific study of a [[Bird ringing|marked]] population by the [[University of Otago]] during a contemporary 1080 poison operation using cereal baits showed no negative impact on robins and suggested a likely population increase by reducing predation pressure from introduced mammals.<ref name=\"TVNZ One News\">{{cite news |url=http://tvnz.co.nz/national-news/study-finds-1080-has-positive-effect-bird-population-video-4844337 |title=Study finds 1080 has positive effect on bird population |author=TVNZ |date=22 April 2012 |work=[[TVNZ]] |accessdate=26 April 2012}}</ref><!-- DEAD LINK Schadewinkel et al. |title=The effect of aerial application of 1080 cereal baits for possum control on South Island robin (Petroica australis) in the Silver Peaks, Dunedin'|url=http://tbfree.org.nz/Portals/0/Research/1080%20-%20robin%20report_final-revised.pdf -->\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.doc.govt.nz/conservation/native-animals/birds/land-birds/nz-robin-toutouwai/ New Zealand Robin] on [[Department of Conservation (New Zealand)|Department of Conservation]] website\n* [http://www.nzbirds.com/birds/toutouwai.html Factsheet on toutouwai, the New Zealand robin] at NZBirds.com\n* [http://www.teara.govt.nz/en/1966/robin/1/ Information about New Zealand robins] on [[Te Ara: The Encyclopedia of New Zealand|Te Ara]]\n* [http://www.doc.org.nz/upload/documents/science-and-technical/docts13.pdf Protocols for monitoring New Zealand robins(Petroica australis)] - [[Department of Conservation (New Zealand)|Department of Conservation]] Technical Series No. 13\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=bwLBfaX4VjE/ Video footage of New Zealand robins] on the [[Animal Health Board (New Zealand)|Animal Health Board]] YouTube Channel\n\n{{Petroicidae}}\n{{Birds of New Zealand}}\n{{Portal bar|Birds|New Zealand}}\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q1051396}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:robin, South Island}}\n[[Category:Petroica|South Island robin]]\n[[Category:Birds of the South Island]]\n[[Category:Endemic fauna of New Zealand]]\n[[Category:Birds described in 1788|South Island robin]]\n[[Category:Taxa named by Anders Sparrman]]\n", "name_user": "Rogermccart", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eTaxonomy:ce", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/South_Island_robin"}
{"title_page": "Douglas V. Mastriano", "text_new": "{{short description|American writer and politician}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| image         =Mastriano 2015.JPG\n| name          =Douglas V. Mastriano\n| state_senate  =Pennsylvania\n| district      =[[Pennsylvania Senate, District 33|33rd]]\n| term_start    =June 10, 2019\n| term_end      =\n| predecessor   =[[Richard Alloway]] \n| successor     =\n| birth_date    ={{birth date and age|1964|1|2}}\n| birth_place   = \n| death_date    = \n| death_place   = \n| party         = [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]\n| alma_mater    =[[Eastern University (United States)|Eastern University]]<br>[[University of New Brunswick]] (Ph.D.) \n| occupation    = Politician, Writer, Historian, [[Colonel|Ret. Col.]]\n| spouse        = \n| children      = 1 son, Josiah<ref name=Colby/><ref name=Hardy9/><ref name=Hardy13/>\n| residence     = [[Greene Township, Franklin County, Pennsylvania]]\n| religion      = \n| website       ={{URL|http://www.fight4pa.com}}<br>{{URL|http://www.sgtyorkdiscovery.com/}} \n|allegiance    = {{flag|United States}}\n|branch        = {{flag|United States Army}}\n|rank = {{Dodseal|USAO6}} [[Colonel (United States)|Colonel]]\n|serviceyears = 1986-2017\n}}\n\n'''Douglas Vincent Mastriano''', Ph.D. (born January 2, 1964), is an American military historian and politician. He is a retired [[Colonel (United States)|Colonel]] of the [[United States Army]] and is the state senator for the [[Pennsylvania Senate, District 33|33rd District]] in Pennsylvania. A [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]], he previously ran as a candidate for [[United States House of Representatives|U.S. Representative]] in {{ushr|PA|13}} before winning a special election in 2019 to replace the retiring [[Richard Alloway|Rich Alloway]]. He has written two books, one of which is a biography of the highly decorated [[World War I]] soldier [[Sergeant Alvin York]]. He has also led the development of research reports and strategy recommendations for the [[U.S. Army War College]].\n\n==Military career==\nMastriano was commissioned in the [[United States Army]] in 1986. He started his military career in [[Nuremberg, Germany]], with the [[2nd Cavalry Regiment (United States)|2nd Armored Cavalry Regiment]] in the area of the [[West German]] borders with [[East Germany]] and [[Czechoslovakia]].<ref name=Colby/> Mastriano also served four years at the [[NATO]] Land Headquarters in [[Heidelberg, Germany]].<ref name=stripes>{{cite web |url=http://www.stripes.com/news/officer-says-he-s-pinpointed-sgt-york-s-stand-1.79280 |title=Officer says he's pinpointed York's stand |last=Montgomery |first=Nancy |date=September 26, 2008 |newspaper=[[Stars and Stripes (newspaper)|Stars and Stripes]] |access-date=April 29, 2015}}</ref> While serving along the East German and Czechoslovakian borders, he witnessed the end of the Cold War and thereafter deployed to Iraq for Operation Desert Storm (1991) to liberate Kuwait. His regiment led the attack against Saddam\u2019s elite Republican Guard forces. Doug went on to serve in Washington, DC, the 3rd Infantry Division and US Army Europe.  After 9/11, Mastriano was the lead planner for the operation to invade Iraq via Turkey.  He served four years with NATO and deployed three times to Afghanistan.  Mastriano was the director of NATO\u2019s Joint Intelligence Center in Afghanistan, leading 80 people from 18 nations.  On his own initiative, Doug led seven relief operations to help Afghan orphans.  He completed his career as a Professor of the U.S. Army War College (PAWC), Carlisle, PA, and taught Strategic Studies at the Master Degree level to the next generation of senior leaders.He retired in 2017 at the rank of Colonel.<ref name=Hardy9/><ref name=Hardy13/>\n\n==Political career==\nOn February 13, 2018, at the Otterbein Church in [[Waynesboro, Pennsylvania]], Mastriano announced his candidacy for [[United States House of Representatives|U.S. Representative]] for {{ushr|PA|9}}, a seat being vacated by the retiring congressman [[Bill Shuster]].<ref name=Hardy9>{{cite news |last=Hardy |first=Shawn |title=Mastriano to Run for Congress |url=http://www.therecordherald.com/news/20180209/mastriano-to-run-for-congress |accessdate=February 16, 2018 |newspaper=[[The Record Herald]] |date=February 9, 2018}}</ref><ref name=Hardy13>{{cite news |last=Hardy |first=Shawn |title=Franklin County man running for Shuster's seat |url=http://www.echo-pilot.com/news/20180213/franklin-county-man-running-for-shusters-seat |access-date=February 16, 2018 |work=[[The Echo-Pilot]] |date=February 13, 2018}}</ref> Less than a week after his announcement, the [[Supreme Court of Pennsylvania]] redrew the congressional district map of Pennsylvania after ruling the previous map unconstitutional (due to [[gerrymandering]] by the majority Republican Party), and the area previously covered by the 9th district corresponds most closely to the new 13th district, so Mastriano became a candidate for {{ushr|PA|13}}.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2018/02/19/upshot/pennsylvania-new-house-districts-gerrymandering.html|title=The New Pennsylvania Congressional Map, District by District|first1=Nate|last1=Cohn |last2=Bloch |first2=Matthew |last3=Quealy |first3=Kevin |date=February 19, 2018|publisher=|work=[[The New York Times]] |access-date=March 30, 2018}}</ref> Mastriano ultimately finished fourth of the eight candidates in the primary election, receiving a total of 10,509 votes.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ballotpedia.org/Pennsylvania%27s_13th_Congressional_District_election,_2018|title=Pennsylvania's 13th Congressional District election, 2018|website=Ballotpedia}}</ref>\n\nOn January 22, 2019, Mastriano announced that he intended to run for the [[Pennsylvania State Senate|State Senate]] seat being vacated by [[Rich Alloway]] in the [[Pennsylvania Senate, District 33|33rd District]], saying he \"can't, in good conscience, stand aside,\" wanting to \"serve his country in a new way.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.therecordherald.com/news/20190122/doug-mastriano-announces-bid-for-state-senate |title=Doug Mastriano announces bid for state Senate |date=January 22, 2019 |publisher=The Record Herald}}</ref>  Mastriano overwhelmingly won the Republican nomination for the May 21 election at a party conference held in Gettysburg on March 30, 2019.\n\n\"Doug Mastriano is the kind of conservative candidate that reflects the values of Southcentral Pennsylvania and will be a key asset in helping advance the Republican agenda in Harrisburg,\" said Republican Party of Pennsylvania Chairman Val DiGiorgio.<ref>{{cite news |last=Rose |first=Andrea |date=April 1, 2019 |title=Doug Mastriano named Republican nominee for the 33rd Senatorial District to replace retired Sen. Rich Alloway |url=https://www.therecordherald.com/news/20190401/doug-mastriano-named-republican-nominee-for-33rd-senatorial-district-to-replace-retired-sen-rich-alloway |work=[[The Record Herald]] |location= Waynesboro, PA}}</ref>\n\nOn May 21, 2019, Mastriano defeated Democrat Sarah Hammond to win the special election in the [[Pennsylvania Senate, District 33|33rd District]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://fox43.com/2019/05/22/republican-candidate-doug-mastriano-wins-33rd-district-state-senate-seat/|title=Republican candidate Doug Mastriano wins 33rd District State Senate seat|date=2019-05-22|website=WPMT FOX43|language=en|access-date=2019-06-10}}</ref> Mastriano was sworn into the Pennsylvania Senate on June 10.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.indianagazette.com/news/pittman-takes-seat-in-harrisburg/article_0b8aa992-8bad-11e9-a6ab-13742b5383b3.html|title=Pittman takes seat in Harrisburg|last=pcloonan@indianagazette.net|first=PATRICK CLOONAN|website=The Indiana Gazette Online|language=en|access-date=2019-06-10}}</ref>\n\n\n==Controversy==\n\nOn March 17, 2020, Mastriano suggested minor suspension of a part of [[HIPAA|HIPAA]] to allow the Department of Health share more [[Covid-19|Covid-19]] data. At the time, Secretary Levine (Secretary of Health) only provided state wide numbers, not by county.  In his proposal Mastriano stated he wanted to allow the Secretary of Health to provide more data in order to protect the health of all Pennsylvanians.  However, Dr. Levine, the Pennsylvania Secretary of Health stated that he was not using HIPAA to prevent the sharing of COVID-19 life saving health information, but rather a 1955 PA law.  Mastriano did not submit any legislation regarding HIPAA and in response to Dr. Levine's clarification, did nothing in regards to HIPAA and instead introduced legislation to update the 1955 law to allow accommodation for future public safety health pandemics.  <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.abc27.com/news/local/harrisburg/midstate-lawmaker-urging-suspension-of-hipaa-protections-among-covid19-outbreak/|title=Midstate lawmaker urging suspension of HIPAA protections among COVID19 outbreak|date=March 18, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 28, 2020, during [[Pennsylvania|Pennsylvania]]'s on going [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Pennsylvania|pandemic]] Douglas Mastriano proposed legislation that would allow all PA businesses to reopen. Calling it \"Pennsylvania Healthy Citizens and Healthy Businesses back to work initiative,\" would allow businesses to reopen if they agree to abide by Center of Disease Control mitigation measures to contain the spread of the virus. He said that this provides a safe, fair and balanced approach to reopening businesses.  A process that uses the expert advice of CDC and OSHA to provide direction on how certain businesses can reopen, which will at the same time, protect the health and welfare of our people and our state.  The legislation received broad support and was referred to a senate committee for a vote. <ref>{{cite web |last1=Leigh |first1=Harri |title=Proposed legislation would allow all businesses in PA to reopen. |url=https://www.fox43.com/article/news/health/coronavirus/proposed-legislation-would-allow-all-pa-businesses-to-reopen/521-27482374-63bb-43ca-983d-0c5f063d673d |website=Fox 43 |accessdate=31 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Published works as author==\nMastriano's first book, ''Alvin York: A New Biography of the Hero of the Argonne'' ({{ISBN|978-0813145198}}), was published by the [[University Press of Kentucky]] in 2014.<ref name=northfield>{{cite web |url=http://www.thenorthfieldnews.com/news/2015-02-05/News/Biographer_of_WWI_hero_Sergeant_York_Named_Winner_.html |title=Biographer of WWI hero Sergeant York named Winner of 2015 Colby Award |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date=February 5, 2015 |website=[[Northfield News & Transcript|The Northfield News]] |access-date=April 29, 2015}}</ref> He conducted twelve years of research for the book.<ref name=newyork>{{cite web |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2006/10/26/world/americas/26iht-york.3300183.html |title=Proof offered of Sgt. York's war exploits |last=Smith |first=Craig S. |date=October 26, 2006 |work=[[The New York Times]] |access-date=April 29, 2015}}</ref> In all, Mastriano reportedly spent 2,000 hours doing research on [[Sergeant Alvin York]], including 1,000 hours studying archives in the United States and various parts of Germany including [[Stuttgart]], [[Freiburg im Breisgau|Freiburg]], [[Potsdam]], [[Rottweil]], and [[Ulm]],<ref name=cbn>{{cite web |url=http://www.cbn.com/cbnnews/100571.aspx |title=Army Officer: Sgt. York battle site located |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date=March 25, 2007 |website=[[Christian Broadcasting Network|CBN News]] |access-date=April 29, 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150311142313/http://www.cbn.com/cbnnews/100571.aspx# |archive-date=2015-03-11 |url-status=dead }}</ref> and another 1,000 hours of field research in the [[Forest of Argonne|Argonne Forest]] of France to locate where Alvin York fought. Using terrain analysis, geo-spatial data, and field archaeology, his research team uncovered thousands of artifacts related to York's battle of October 8, 1918.  He said that his interest in York began when he was a child, after having seen ''[[Sergeant York (film)|Sergeant York]]'', an [[Academy Award]] winning 1941 film starring [[Gary Cooper]]. After he joined the Army, his interest in York deepened.<ref name=stripes /> Along with research, the books incorporates forensic study and military terrain analysis.<ref name=northfield />\n\nMastriano's book on York received the 2015 [[Colby Award|William E. Colby Award]] of the William E. Colby Military Writers' Symposium at [[Norwich University]] (an award for a first published work of a military topic author),<ref name=Colby>{{cite web |url=http://colby.norwich.edu/participants/douglas-v-mastriano/ |title=Col Douglas V. Mastriano, PhD |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |website=William E. Colby Military Writers' Symposium, [[Norwich University]] |access-date=April 29, 2015}}</ref> the [[National Museum of the United States Army|Army Historical Foundation]] Award, the [[United States Army War College|US Army War College]] Madigan Award and the 2015 Crader Family Book Prize in American Values.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.broadwayworld.com/bwwbooks/article/Author-Douglas-V-Mastriano-Wins-Crader-Book-Prize-20150424 |title=Author Douglas V. Mastriano Wins Crader Book Prize |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date=May 24, 2015 |website=[[Broadway Books]] |access-date=May 24, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ausa.org/news/2015/Pages/AUSABookWinsFourAwards.aspx |title=AUSA Book Wins Four Awards |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date=May 19, 2015 |website=[[Association of the United States Army]] |access-date=May 24, 2015}}</ref>\n\nMastriano's second book, ''Thunder in the Argonne: A New History of America's Greatest Battle'' ({{ISBN|978-0813175553}}), was published by the University Press of Kentucky in 2018.\n\nMastriano's other published works include:<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.amazon.com/Douglas-V.-Mastriano/e/B00GSPTMFA/|title=Douglas V. Mastriano |website=[[Amazon.com]] |access-date=March 30, 2018}}</ref>\n* ''Project 1704: U.S. Army War College Analysis of Russian Strategy in Eastern Europe, Appropriate U.S. Response, and Implications for U.S. Landpower \u2013 Putin's Rise to Power, Military, Ukraine Crisis'', as project leader for a U.S. Army War College project, 2017<ref>{{cite report |url=https://www.amazon.com/Project-1704-Appropriate-Implications-Landpower/dp/1520122101 |title=Project 1704: U.S. Army War College Analysis of Russian Strategy in Eastern Europe, Appropriate U.S. Response, and Implications for U.S. Landpower \u2013 Putin's Rise to Power, Military, Ukraine Crisis |date=January 13, 2017 |access-date=March 30, 2018}}</ref>\n* ''Project 1721: A U.S. Army War College Assessment on Russian Strategy in Eastern Europe and Recommendations on How to Leverage Landpower to Maintain the Peace'', as project leader for a U.S. Army War College project, 2017<ref>{{cite report |url=https://ssi.armywarcollege.edu/pubs/display.cfm?pubID=1342 |title=Project 1721: A U.S. Army War College Assessment On Russian Strategy In Eastern Europe And Recommendations On How To Leverage Landpower To Maintain The Peace |date=March 22, 2017 |website=[[Strategic Studies Institute]] |access-date=March 30, 2018}}</ref>\n* ''Project 1704: A U.S. Army War College Analysis of Russian Strategy in Eastern Europe, an Appropriate U.S. Response, and the Implications for U.S. Landpower'', as project leader for a U.S. Army War College project, 2015<ref>{{cite report|url=http://www.strategicstudiesinstitute.army.mil/pubs/display.cfm?pubID=1274 |title=Project 1704: A U.S. Army War College Analysis of Russian Strategy in Eastern Europe, an Appropriate U.S. Response, and the Implications for U.S. Landpower |date=March 26, 2015 |website=[[Strategic Studies Institute]] |access-date=March 30, 2018}}</ref>\n* ''Nebuchadnezzar's Sphinx: What Have We Learned from Baghdad's Plan to Take Kuwait?'', a thesis for the School of Advanced Air Power Studies, [[Air University (United States Air Force)|Air University]], [[Maxwell Air Force Base]], [[Montgomery, Alabama]], June 2002<ref>{{cite thesis |last=Mastriano |first=Douglas V. |url=http://www.dtic.mil/dtic/tr/fulltext/u2/a420681.pdf |title=Nebuchadnezzar's Sphinx: What Have We Learned from Baghdad's Plan to Take Kuwait? |publisher=[[Air University (United States Air Force)|Air University]], [[Maxwell Air Force Base]], [[Montgomery, Alabama]] |date=June 2002 |access-date=March 30, 2018}}</ref>\n* ''The Civilian Putsch of 2018: Debunking The Myth of a Civil-Military Leadership Rift'', a research report for the School of Advanced Air Power Studies, Air University, Maxwell Air Force Base, Montgomery, Alabama, April 2001<ref>{{cite report |last=Mastriano |first=Douglas V. |url=http://www.dtic.mil/cgi-bin/GetTRDoc?AD=ADA407262&Location=U2&doc=GetTRDoc.pdf |title=The Civilian Putsch of 2018: Debunking The Myth of a Civil-Military Leadership Rift |publisher=[[Air University (United States Air Force)|Air University]], [[Maxwell Air Force Base]], [[Montgomery, Alabama]] |date=April 2001 |access-date=March 30, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commonscatinline}}\n*[https://kentuckypress.wordpress.com/tag/douglas-v-mastriano/ The Controversy Surrounding Sergeant York: Uncovering the WWI Iconic Hero's Background] at Kentucky Press \n*[http://www.ocfusa.org/articles/leadership-q/#.VUFC-LEo7cs Leadership Q&A] at Officers' Christian Fellowship\n*{{C-SPAN|Douglas Mastriano}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Mastriano, Douglas V.}}\n[[Category:1964 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American military historians]]\n[[Category:American male non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:University of New Brunswick alumni]]\n[[Category:United States Army War College faculty]]\n[[Category:United States Army colonels]]\n[[Category:21st-century American non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:American army personnel of the Gulf War]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American writer and politician}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| image         =Mastriano 2015.JPG\n| name          =Douglas V. Mastriano\n| state_senate  =Pennsylvania\n| district      =[[Pennsylvania Senate, District 33|33rd]]\n| term_start    =June 10, 2019\n| term_end      =\n| predecessor   =[[Richard Alloway]] \n| successor     =\n| birth_date    ={{birth date and age|1964|1|2}}\n| birth_place   = \n| death_date    = \n| death_place   = \n| party         = [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]\n| alma_mater    =[[Eastern University (United States)|Eastern University]]<br>[[University of New Brunswick]] (Ph.D.) \n| occupation    = Politician, Writer, Historian, [[Colonel|Ret. Col.]]\n| spouse        = \n| children      = 1 son, Josiah<ref name=Colby/><ref name=Hardy9/><ref name=Hardy13/>\n| residence     = [[Greene Township, Franklin County, Pennsylvania]]\n| religion      = \n| website       ={{URL|http://www.fight4pa.com}}<br>{{URL|http://www.sgtyorkdiscovery.com/}} \n|allegiance    = {{flag|United States}}\n|branch        = {{flag|United States Army}}\n|rank = {{Dodseal|USAO6}} [[Colonel (United States)|Colonel]]\n|serviceyears = 1986-2017\n}}\n\n'''Douglas Vincent Mastriano''', Ph.D. (born January 2, 1964), is an American military historian and politician. He is a retired [[Colonel (United States)|Colonel]] of the [[United States Army]] and is the state senator for the [[Pennsylvania Senate, District 33|33rd District]] in Pennsylvania. A [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]], he previously ran as a candidate for [[United States House of Representatives|U.S. Representative]] in {{ushr|PA|13}} before winning a special election in 2019 to replace the retiring [[Richard Alloway|Rich Alloway]]. He has written two books, one of which is a biography of the highly decorated [[World War I]] soldier [[Sergeant Alvin York]]. He has also led the development of research reports and strategy recommendations for the [[U.S. Army War College]].\n\n==Military career==\nMastriano was commissioned in the [[United States Army]] in 1986. He started his military career in [[Nuremberg, Germany]], with the [[2nd Cavalry Regiment (United States)|2nd Armored Cavalry Regiment]] in the area of the [[West German]] borders with [[East Germany]] and [[Czechoslovakia]].<ref name=Colby/> Mastriano also served four years at the [[NATO]] Land Headquarters in [[Heidelberg, Germany]].<ref name=stripes>{{cite web |url=http://www.stripes.com/news/officer-says-he-s-pinpointed-sgt-york-s-stand-1.79280 |title=Officer says he's pinpointed York's stand |last=Montgomery |first=Nancy |date=September 26, 2008 |newspaper=[[Stars and Stripes (newspaper)|Stars and Stripes]] |access-date=April 29, 2015}}</ref> While serving along the East German and Czechoslovakian borders, he witnessed the end of the Cold War and thereafter deployed to Iraq for Operation Desert Storm (1991) to liberate Kuwait. His regiment led the attack against Saddam\u2019s elite Republican Guard forces. Doug went on to serve in Washington, DC, the 3rd Infantry Division and US Army Europe.  After 9/11, Mastriano was the lead planner for the operation to invade Iraq via Turkey.  He served four years with NATO and deployed three times to Afghanistan.  Mastriano was the director of NATO\u2019s Joint Intelligence Center in Afghanistan, leading 80 people from 18 nations.  On his own initiative, Doug led seven relief operations to help Afghan orphans.  He completed his career as a Professor of the U.S. Army War College (PAWC), Carlisle, PA, and taught Strategic Studies at the Master Degree level to the next generation of senior leaders.He retired in 2017 at the rank of Colonel.<ref name=Hardy9/><ref name=Hardy13/>\n\n==Political career==\nOn February 13, 2018, at the Otterbein Church in [[Waynesboro, Pennsylvania]], Mastriano announced his candidacy for [[United States House of Representatives|U.S. Representative]] for {{ushr|PA|9}}, a seat being vacated by the retiring congressman [[Bill Shuster]].<ref name=Hardy9>{{cite news |last=Hardy |first=Shawn |title=Mastriano to Run for Congress |url=http://www.therecordherald.com/news/20180209/mastriano-to-run-for-congress |accessdate=February 16, 2018 |newspaper=[[The Record Herald]] |date=February 9, 2018}}</ref><ref name=Hardy13>{{cite news |last=Hardy |first=Shawn |title=Franklin County man running for Shuster's seat |url=http://www.echo-pilot.com/news/20180213/franklin-county-man-running-for-shusters-seat |access-date=February 16, 2018 |work=[[The Echo-Pilot]] |date=February 13, 2018}}</ref> Less than a week after his announcement, the [[Supreme Court of Pennsylvania]] redrew the congressional district map of Pennsylvania after ruling the previous map unconstitutional (due to [[gerrymandering]] by the majority Republican Party), and the area previously covered by the 9th district corresponds most closely to the new 13th district, so Mastriano became a candidate for {{ushr|PA|13}}.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2018/02/19/upshot/pennsylvania-new-house-districts-gerrymandering.html|title=The New Pennsylvania Congressional Map, District by District|first1=Nate|last1=Cohn |last2=Bloch |first2=Matthew |last3=Quealy |first3=Kevin |date=February 19, 2018|publisher=|work=[[The New York Times]] |access-date=March 30, 2018}}</ref> Mastriano ultimately finished fourth of the eight candidates in the primary election, receiving a total of 10,509 votes.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ballotpedia.org/Pennsylvania%27s_13th_Congressional_District_election,_2018|title=Pennsylvania's 13th Congressional District election, 2018|website=Ballotpedia}}</ref>\n\nOn January 22, 2019, Mastriano announced that he intended to run for the [[Pennsylvania State Senate|State Senate]] seat being vacated by [[Rich Alloway]] in the [[Pennsylvania Senate, District 33|33rd District]], saying he \"can't, in good conscience, stand aside,\" wanting to \"serve his country in a new way.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.therecordherald.com/news/20190122/doug-mastriano-announces-bid-for-state-senate |title=Doug Mastriano announces bid for state Senate |date=January 22, 2019 |publisher=The Record Herald}}</ref>  Mastriano overwhelmingly won the Republican nomination for the May 21 election at a party conference held in Gettysburg on March 30, 2019.\n\n\"Doug Mastriano is the kind of conservative candidate that reflects the values of Southcentral Pennsylvania and will be a key asset in helping advance the Republican agenda in Harrisburg,\" said Republican Party of Pennsylvania Chairman Val DiGiorgio.<ref>{{cite news |last=Rose |first=Andrea |date=April 1, 2019 |title=Doug Mastriano named Republican nominee for the 33rd Senatorial District to replace retired Sen. Rich Alloway |url=https://www.therecordherald.com/news/20190401/doug-mastriano-named-republican-nominee-for-33rd-senatorial-district-to-replace-retired-sen-rich-alloway |work=[[The Record Herald]] |location= Waynesboro, PA}}</ref>\n\nOn May 21, 2019, Mastriano defeated Democrat Sarah Hammond to win the special election in the [[Pennsylvania Senate, District 33|33rd District]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://fox43.com/2019/05/22/republican-candidate-doug-mastriano-wins-33rd-district-state-senate-seat/|title=Republican candidate Doug Mastriano wins 33rd District State Senate seat|date=2019-05-22|website=WPMT FOX43|language=en|access-date=2019-06-10}}</ref> Mastriano was sworn into the Pennsylvania Senate on June 10.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.indianagazette.com/news/pittman-takes-seat-in-harrisburg/article_0b8aa992-8bad-11e9-a6ab-13742b5383b3.html|title=Pittman takes seat in Harrisburg|last=pcloonan@indianagazette.net|first=PATRICK CLOONAN|website=The Indiana Gazette Online|language=en|access-date=2019-06-10}}</ref>\n\n\n==Controversy==\n\nOn March 17, 2020, Mastriano called for a suspension of [[HIPAA|HIPAA]] in order to publicly identify individuals infected with [[Covid-19|Covid-19]]. In his proposal Mastriano stated he wanted to publish the names and addresses of those who have been infected.  However, Dr. Levine, the Pennsylvania Secretary of Health stated that he was not using HIPAA to prevent the sharing of COVID-19 life saving health information, but rather a 1955 PA law.  Mastriano did not submit any legislation regarding HIPAA and in response to Dr. Levine, introduced legislation to update the 1955 law to allow accommodation for any future public safety health pandemics.  <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.abc27.com/news/local/harrisburg/midstate-lawmaker-urging-suspension-of-hipaa-protections-among-covid19-outbreak/|title=Midstate lawmaker urging suspension of HIPAA protections among COVID19 outbreak|date=March 18, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 28, 2020, during [[Pennsylvania|Pennsylvania]]'s on going [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Pennsylvania|pandemic]] Douglas Mastriano proposed legislation that would allow all PA businesses to reopen. <ref>{{cite web |last1=Leigh |first1=Harri |title=Proposed legislation would allow all businesses in PA to reopen. |url=https://www.fox43.com/article/news/health/coronavirus/proposed-legislation-would-allow-all-pa-businesses-to-reopen/521-27482374-63bb-43ca-983d-0c5f063d673d |website=Fox 43 |accessdate=31 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Published works as author==\nMastriano's first book, ''Alvin York: A New Biography of the Hero of the Argonne'' ({{ISBN|978-0813145198}}), was published by the [[University Press of Kentucky]] in 2014.<ref name=northfield>{{cite web |url=http://www.thenorthfieldnews.com/news/2015-02-05/News/Biographer_of_WWI_hero_Sergeant_York_Named_Winner_.html |title=Biographer of WWI hero Sergeant York named Winner of 2015 Colby Award |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date=February 5, 2015 |website=[[Northfield News & Transcript|The Northfield News]] |access-date=April 29, 2015}}</ref> He conducted twelve years of research for the book.<ref name=newyork>{{cite web |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2006/10/26/world/americas/26iht-york.3300183.html |title=Proof offered of Sgt. York's war exploits |last=Smith |first=Craig S. |date=October 26, 2006 |work=[[The New York Times]] |access-date=April 29, 2015}}</ref> In all, Mastriano reportedly spent 2,000 hours doing research on [[Sergeant Alvin York]], including 1,000 hours studying archives in the United States and various parts of Germany including [[Stuttgart]], [[Freiburg im Breisgau|Freiburg]], [[Potsdam]], [[Rottweil]], and [[Ulm]],<ref name=cbn>{{cite web |url=http://www.cbn.com/cbnnews/100571.aspx |title=Army Officer: Sgt. York battle site located |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date=March 25, 2007 |website=[[Christian Broadcasting Network|CBN News]] |access-date=April 29, 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150311142313/http://www.cbn.com/cbnnews/100571.aspx# |archive-date=2015-03-11 |url-status=dead }}</ref> and another 1,000 hours of field research in the [[Forest of Argonne|Argonne Forest]] of France to locate where Alvin York fought. Using terrain analysis, geo-spatial data, and field archaeology, his research team uncovered thousands of artifacts related to York's battle of October 8, 1918.  He said that his interest in York began when he was a child, after having seen ''[[Sergeant York (film)|Sergeant York]]'', an [[Academy Award]] winning 1941 film starring [[Gary Cooper]]. After he joined the Army, his interest in York deepened.<ref name=stripes /> Along with research, the books incorporates forensic study and military terrain analysis.<ref name=northfield />\n\nMastriano's book on York received the 2015 [[Colby Award|William E. Colby Award]] of the William E. Colby Military Writers' Symposium at [[Norwich University]] (an award for a first published work of a military topic author),<ref name=Colby>{{cite web |url=http://colby.norwich.edu/participants/douglas-v-mastriano/ |title=Col Douglas V. Mastriano, PhD |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |website=William E. Colby Military Writers' Symposium, [[Norwich University]] |access-date=April 29, 2015}}</ref> the [[National Museum of the United States Army|Army Historical Foundation]] Award, the [[United States Army War College|US Army War College]] Madigan Award and the 2015 Crader Family Book Prize in American Values.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.broadwayworld.com/bwwbooks/article/Author-Douglas-V-Mastriano-Wins-Crader-Book-Prize-20150424 |title=Author Douglas V. Mastriano Wins Crader Book Prize |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date=May 24, 2015 |website=[[Broadway Books]] |access-date=May 24, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ausa.org/news/2015/Pages/AUSABookWinsFourAwards.aspx |title=AUSA Book Wins Four Awards |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date=May 19, 2015 |website=[[Association of the United States Army]] |access-date=May 24, 2015}}</ref>\n\nMastriano's second book, ''Thunder in the Argonne: A New History of America's Greatest Battle'' ({{ISBN|978-0813175553}}), was published by the University Press of Kentucky in 2018.\n\nMastriano's other published works include:<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.amazon.com/Douglas-V.-Mastriano/e/B00GSPTMFA/|title=Douglas V. Mastriano |website=[[Amazon.com]] |access-date=March 30, 2018}}</ref>\n* ''Project 1704: U.S. Army War College Analysis of Russian Strategy in Eastern Europe, Appropriate U.S. Response, and Implications for U.S. Landpower \u2013 Putin's Rise to Power, Military, Ukraine Crisis'', as project leader for a U.S. Army War College project, 2017<ref>{{cite report |url=https://www.amazon.com/Project-1704-Appropriate-Implications-Landpower/dp/1520122101 |title=Project 1704: U.S. Army War College Analysis of Russian Strategy in Eastern Europe, Appropriate U.S. Response, and Implications for U.S. Landpower \u2013 Putin's Rise to Power, Military, Ukraine Crisis |date=January 13, 2017 |access-date=March 30, 2018}}</ref>\n* ''Project 1721: A U.S. Army War College Assessment on Russian Strategy in Eastern Europe and Recommendations on How to Leverage Landpower to Maintain the Peace'', as project leader for a U.S. Army War College project, 2017<ref>{{cite report |url=https://ssi.armywarcollege.edu/pubs/display.cfm?pubID=1342 |title=Project 1721: A U.S. Army War College Assessment On Russian Strategy In Eastern Europe And Recommendations On How To Leverage Landpower To Maintain The Peace |date=March 22, 2017 |website=[[Strategic Studies Institute]] |access-date=March 30, 2018}}</ref>\n* ''Project 1704: A U.S. Army War College Analysis of Russian Strategy in Eastern Europe, an Appropriate U.S. Response, and the Implications for U.S. Landpower'', as project leader for a U.S. Army War College project, 2015<ref>{{cite report|url=http://www.strategicstudiesinstitute.army.mil/pubs/display.cfm?pubID=1274 |title=Project 1704: A U.S. Army War College Analysis of Russian Strategy in Eastern Europe, an Appropriate U.S. Response, and the Implications for U.S. Landpower |date=March 26, 2015 |website=[[Strategic Studies Institute]] |access-date=March 30, 2018}}</ref>\n* ''Nebuchadnezzar's Sphinx: What Have We Learned from Baghdad's Plan to Take Kuwait?'', a thesis for the School of Advanced Air Power Studies, [[Air University (United States Air Force)|Air University]], [[Maxwell Air Force Base]], [[Montgomery, Alabama]], June 2002<ref>{{cite thesis |last=Mastriano |first=Douglas V. |url=http://www.dtic.mil/dtic/tr/fulltext/u2/a420681.pdf |title=Nebuchadnezzar's Sphinx: What Have We Learned from Baghdad's Plan to Take Kuwait? |publisher=[[Air University (United States Air Force)|Air University]], [[Maxwell Air Force Base]], [[Montgomery, Alabama]] |date=June 2002 |access-date=March 30, 2018}}</ref>\n* ''The Civilian Putsch of 2018: Debunking The Myth of a Civil-Military Leadership Rift'', a research report for the School of Advanced Air Power Studies, Air University, Maxwell Air Force Base, Montgomery, Alabama, April 2001<ref>{{cite report |last=Mastriano |first=Douglas V. |url=http://www.dtic.mil/cgi-bin/GetTRDoc?AD=ADA407262&Location=U2&doc=GetTRDoc.pdf |title=The Civilian Putsch of 2018: Debunking The Myth of a Civil-Military Leadership Rift |publisher=[[Air University (United States Air Force)|Air University]], [[Maxwell Air Force Base]], [[Montgomery, Alabama]] |date=April 2001 |access-date=March 30, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commonscatinline}}\n*[https://kentuckypress.wordpress.com/tag/douglas-v-mastriano/ The Controversy Surrounding Sergeant York: Uncovering the WWI Iconic Hero's Background] at Kentucky Press \n*[http://www.ocfusa.org/articles/leadership-q/#.VUFC-LEo7cs Leadership Q&A] at Officers' Christian Fellowship\n*{{C-SPAN|Douglas Mastriano}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Mastriano, Douglas V.}}\n[[Category:1964 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American military historians]]\n[[Category:American male non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:University of New Brunswick alumni]]\n[[Category:United States Army War College faculty]]\n[[Category:United States Army colonels]]\n[[Category:21st-century American non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:American army personnel of the Gulf War]]\n", "name_user": "DrWillow", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eControversy:Factual information provided on the public discourse surrounding this legislation", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Douglas_V._Mastriano"}
