{"title_page": "Charleston Community Unit School District 1", "text_new": "{{Infobox school district\n|name                = Charleston Community Unit School District 1\n|logo                = \n|motto               = \u201cA 1st rate public education for a caring community!\u201d\n|type                = [[Unified School District]]\n|grades              = PreK-12\n|established         = <!-- {{Start date|}} -->\n|closed              = \n|region              = [[Coles County, Illinois|Coles County]], [[Illinois]]\n|country             = [[United States]]\n|location            = 410 West Polk Ave<br>[[Charleston, Illinois|Charleston]], [[Illinois]]\n|coordinates         = <!-- {{Coord|||dim:250_region:US-_type:edu|name=District office|display=inline,title}} -->\n|president           = \n|vice-president      = \n|superintendent      = Todd Vilardo\n|asst_superintendent = \n|schools             = [[Charleston High School (Illinois)]] <br> Charleston Middle School (7-8) <br> Jefferson Elementary School (4-6) <br> Carl Sandberg Elementary School (1-3) <br> Mark Twain Elementary School (PreK and K) <br> Ashmore Elementary School (PreK-4)\n|budget              = \n|us_nces_district_id = <!-- {{NCES District ID||district_name=|access_date=}} -->\n|students            = \n|faculty             = \n|teachers            = \n|staff               = \n|ratio               = \n|conference          = \n|website             = http://www.charleston.k12.il.us\n}}\n'''Charleston Community Unit School District 1''' is a [[unified school district]] based in [[Charleston, Illinois|Charleston]], the county seat of [[Coles County, Illinois|Coles County]], [[Illinois]].\n\n==History==\nIt was created through the consolidation of the charter school district it was formed from and over sixty-seven other school districts in the area. Charleston Community Unit School District 1 is a conglomerate of six schools, with all but one located in Charleston itself: four elementary schools, one middle school, and one high school form the makeup of the district. Education begins at a prekindergarten level, and those living in the Charleston area attend Mark Twain Elementary School, which prepares early youth for schooling by taking them through prekindergarten and kindergarten under the supervision of principal Terry Diss.<ref>[http://www.charleston.k12.il.us/mtes/ MTES Administration Listing], retrieved 2008-6-15</ref> Students who live in the far east reaches of Coles County may attend Ashmore Elementary School, which is based in a northeasterly village [[Ashmore, Illinois|by the same name]]; Ashmore's distance from the other schools permits it to educate a larger range of students for the sake of efficiency. The school educates students from kindergarten through grade four, and also runs a prekindergarten program. Ashmore is also governed by Terry Diss.<ref>[http://www.charleston.k12.il.us/aes/ AES Main Page (click on administration option on bar)], retrieved 2008-6-15</ref> Students who graduate from Mark Twain move onwards to Carl Sandburg Elementary School, which educates those in grades one, two, and three under principal Chad Burgett.<ref>[http://www.charleston.k12.il.us/cses/adminstaff.html CSES Administration Listing], retrieved 2008-6-15</ref> At Jefferson Elementary School in Charleston, the student bodies from both Carl Sandburg Elementary School and Ashmore Elementary School are consolidated. Students from grades four through six are taught in the facility under the supervision of principal Deborah Poffinbarger.<ref>[http://www.charleston.k12.il.us/jes/staff.htm JES Staff Listing], retrieved 2008-6-15</ref> District students graduating from Jefferson are moved to Charleston Middle School, where they are taught as seventh and eighth graders; the school principal here is Sandy Wilson.<ref>[http://www.charleston.k12.il.us/cms/staff.htm CMS Staff Listing], retrieved 2008-6-15</ref> The last branch of education that Charleston's school district can provide is the education of adolescents in the grades nine through twelve at Charleston High School, which is run by principal Trevor Doughty.<ref>[http://www.charleston.k12.il.us/chs/adminstaff.html CHS Administrative Staff] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080422200856/http://www.charleston.k12.il.us/chs/adminstaff.html |date=April 22, 2008 }}, retrieved 2008-6-15</ref> The superintendent of the schools in the district as of the 2007-08 school year was Dr. William Hill, although is considered as an interim;<ref>[http://www.charleston.k12.il.us/adminstaff.htm Charleston CUSD 1 Administrative Staff] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080422201045/http://www.charleston.k12.il.us/adminstaff.htm |date=April 22, 2008 }}, retrieved 2008-6-15</ref>lastly, the mascots of the district and its middle and high schools are the [[Troy|Trojans]], while the mascot of Jefferson Elementary School is the [[bulldog]].\nThere are numerous clubs at Charleston High School; examples include a branch of the [[International Thespian Society]], a branch of the [[National FFA Organization|FFA]], a newspaper club, and various foreign language honor societies. The high school also sports a junior varsity and varsity [[Scholastic Bowl]] team, and runs a school band; the band also runs an extension known as the Flag Corps, upon which athletic band members participate at sporting events.<ref>[http://www.charleston.k12.il.us/chs/clubsnactivities.html CHS Clubs and Activities Listing], retrieved 2008-6-15</ref>\n\nCharleston Middle School also runs a variety of extracurricular activities, ranging from athletic teams such as softball, basketball, and cheerleading, to other activities, such as a newspaper, and a student council. The middle school's [[Scholastic Bowl]] team advanced as far as to achieve fourth place at the State competition in the year 2007 and went to regionals in 2016.<ref>[http://www.charleston.k12.il.us/cms/extracurricular.htm Extracurricular Activities at CMS], retrieved 2008-6-15</ref>\n\nIn the 2007-08 school year, students at Jefferson Middle School participated in a drive to send supplies to troops on the battlefront. The project, known as \"Jefferson Elementary Thanking Soldiers\" (or JETS) was organized and coordinated by a then-sixth grader named Carley Coffey, and grew to become a communitywide effort.<ref>[http://www.jg-tc.com/articles/2007/12/06/news/doc4757703379600715674084.txt Journal Gazette-Times Courier Online:] December 7, 2007</ref>\n\n==External links==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20080630015046/http://www.charleston.k12.il.us/index.html District website]\n\n==References==\n\n{{reflist|2}}\n*[http://www.greatschools.net/schools.page?district=330&state=IL GreatSchools.net Information on Charleston Cusd 1 Schools], retrieved 2008-6-15\n\n[[Category:Education in Coles County, Illinois]]\n[[Category:School districts in Illinois]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox school district\n|name                = Charleston Community Unit School District 1\n|logo                = \n|motto               = \u201cA 1st rate public education for a caring community!\u201d\n|type                = [[Unified School District]]\n|grades              = PreK-12\n|established         = <!-- {{Start date|}} -->\n|closed              = \n|region              = [[Coles County, Illinois|Coles County]], [[Illinois]]\n|country             = [[United States]]\n|location            = 410 West Polk Ave<br>[[Charleston, Illinois|Charleston]], [[Illinois]]\n|coordinates         = <!-- {{Coord|||dim:250_region:US-_type:edu|name=District office|display=inline,title}} -->\n|president           = \n|vice-president      = \n|superintendent      = Todd Vilardo\n|asst_superintendent = \n|schools             = [[Charleston High School (Illinois)]] <br> Charleston Middle School (7-8) <br> Jefferson Elementary School (4-6) <br> Carl Sandberg Elementary School (1-3) <br> Mark Twain Elementary School (PreK and K) <br> Ashmore Elementary School (PreK-4)\n|budget              = \n|us_nces_district_id = <!-- {{NCES District ID||district_name=|access_date=}} -->\n|students            = \n|faculty             = \n|teachers            = \n|staff               = \n|ratio               = \n|conference          = \n|website             = http://www.charleston.k12.il.us\n}}\n'''Charleston Community Unit School District 1''' is a [[unified school district]] based in [[Charleston, Illinois|Charleston]], the county seat of [[Coles County, Illinois|Coles County]], [[Illinois]].\n\n==History==\nit was created through the consolidation of the charter school district it was formed from and over sixty-seven other school districts in the area. Charleston Community Unit School District 1 is a conglomerate of six schools, with all but one located in Charleston itself: four elementary schools, one middle school, and one high school form the makeup of the district. Education begins at a prekindergarten level, and those living in the Charleston area attend Mark Twain Elementary School, which prepares early youth for schooling by taking them through prekindergarten and kindergarten under the supervision of principal Terry Diss.<ref>[http://www.charleston.k12.il.us/mtes/ MTES Administration Listing], retrieved 2008-6-15</ref> Students who live in the far east reaches of Coles County may attend Ashmore Elementary School, which is based in a northeasterly village [[Ashmore, Illinois|by the same name]]; Ashmore's distance from the other schools permits it to educate a larger range of students for the sake of efficiency. The school educates students from kindergarten through grade four, and also runs a prekindergarten program. Ashmore is also governed by Terry Diss.<ref>[http://www.charleston.k12.il.us/aes/ AES Main Page (click on administration option on bar)], retrieved 2008-6-15</ref> Students who graduate from Mark Twain move onwards to Carl Sandburg Elementary School, which educates those in grades one, two, and three under principal Chad Burgett.<ref>[http://www.charleston.k12.il.us/cses/adminstaff.html CSES Administration Listing], retrieved 2008-6-15</ref> At Jefferson Elementary School in Charleston, the student bodies from both Carl Sandburg Elementary School and Ashmore Elementary School are consolidated. Students from grades four through six are taught in the facility under the supervision of principal Deborah Poffinbarger.<ref>[http://www.charleston.k12.il.us/jes/staff.htm JES Staff Listing], retrieved 2008-6-15</ref> District students graduating from Jefferson are moved to Charleston Middle School, where they are taught as seventh and eighth graders; the school principal here is Sandy Wilson.<ref>[http://www.charleston.k12.il.us/cms/staff.htm CMS Staff Listing], retrieved 2008-6-15</ref> The last branch of education that Charleston's school district can provide is the education of adolescents in the grades nine through twelve at Charleston High School, which is run by principal Trevor Doughty.<ref>[http://www.charleston.k12.il.us/chs/adminstaff.html CHS Administrative Staff] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080422200856/http://www.charleston.k12.il.us/chs/adminstaff.html |date=April 22, 2008 }}, retrieved 2008-6-15</ref> The superintendent of the schools in the district as of the 2007-08 school year was Dr. William Hill, although is considered as an interim;<ref>[http://www.charleston.k12.il.us/adminstaff.htm Charleston CUSD 1 Administrative Staff] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080422201045/http://www.charleston.k12.il.us/adminstaff.htm |date=April 22, 2008 }}, retrieved 2008-6-15</ref>lastly, the mascots of the district and its middle and high schools are the [[Troy|Trojans]], while the mascot of Jefferson Elementary School is the [[bulldog]].\nThere are numerous clubs at Charleston High School; examples include a branch of the [[International Thespian Society]], a branch of the [[National FFA Organization|FFA]], a newspaper club, and various foreign language honor societies. The high school also sports a junior varsity and varsity [[Scholastic Bowl]] team, and runs a school band; the band also runs an extension known as the Flag Corps, upon which athletic band members participate at sporting events.<ref>[http://www.charleston.k12.il.us/chs/clubsnactivities.html CHS Clubs and Activities Listing], retrieved 2008-6-15</ref>\n\nCharleston Middle School also runs a variety of extracurricular activities, ranging from athletic teams such as softball, basketball, and cheerleading, to other activities, such as a newspaper, and a student council. The middle school's [[Scholastic Bowl]] team advanced as far as to achieve fourth place at the State competition in the year 2007 and went to regionals in 2016.<ref>[http://www.charleston.k12.il.us/cms/extracurricular.htm Extracurricular Activities at CMS], retrieved 2008-6-15</ref>\n\nIn the 2007-08 school year, students at Jefferson Middle School participated in a drive to send supplies to troops on the battlefront. The project, known as \"Jefferson Elementary Thanking Soldiers\" (or JETS) was organized and coordinated by a then-sixth grader named Carley Coffey, and grew to become a communitywide effort.<ref>[http://www.jg-tc.com/articles/2007/12/06/news/doc4757703379600715674084.txt Journal Gazette-Times Courier Online:] December 7, 2007</ref>\n\n==External links==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20080630015046/http://www.charleston.k12.il.us/index.html District website]\n\n==References==\n\n{{reflist|2}}\n*[http://www.greatschools.net/schools.page?district=330&state=IL GreatSchools.net Information on Charleston Cusd 1 Schools], retrieved 2008-6-15\n\n[[Category:Education in Coles County, Illinois]]\n[[Category:School districts in Illinois]]\n", "name_user": "Throne dwarf", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eHistory", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Charleston_Community_Unit_School_District_1"}
{"title_page": "List of Disney Channel original films", "text_new": "{{About|Disney Channel original movies|Disney Channel series|List of Disney Channel series}}\n{{short description|Wikipedia list article}}\n{{Use mdy dates|cs1-dates=ly|date=August 2019}}\nMany [[television movie|television films]] have been produced for the United States [[cable network]], [[Disney Channel]], since the service's inception in 1983. In its early years, such movies were referred to as '''Disney Channel Premiere Films'''. From late 1997 onward, these television films have been branded under the '''Disney Channel Original Movies''' ('''DCOM''') banner.<ref name=\"mtv\">{{cite news|author=Stacey Grant|title=14 Films Everyone Mistakes For Disney Channel Original Movies|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/2752917/movies-that-are-not-disney-channel-original-movies-dcoms/|accessdate=2017-03-14|work=MTV News|date=March 11, 2016|language=en}}</ref>\n\nMost of these films were subsequently released on [[VHS]], [[DVD]], or, more recently, [[Blu-ray]]. However, many more in the Disney television film library have never been released in any home video format. Originally, DCOMs were released on DVD months after they premiered on Disney Channel, but starting with ''[[Princess Protection Program]]'', DVDs for DCOMs have been released one week after they premiere on Disney Channel. Also, although DCOMs have been produced in widescreen HD format since mid-2005, the 2009 release of ''[[Princess Protection Program]]'' became the first DCOM to receive a widescreen DVD transfer.\n\nThe highest-rated premiere for the brand came in August 2007, when ''[[High School Musical 2]]'' set a record for basic cable with 17.2 million viewers. The second highest-rated premiere is held by ''[[Wizards of Waverly Place: The Movie]]'', which premiered with 11.4 million viewers. Other major DCOM franchises include ''[[Camp Rock]]'', ''[[The Cheetah Girls (film series)|The Cheetah Girls]]'', ''Twitches'', ''[[Halloweentown (film series)|Halloweentown]]'', the ''[[Teen Beach Movie|Teen Beach]]'' films, the ''[[Zenon: Girl of the 21st Century (film)|Zenon]]'' trilogy, and ''[[Descendants (2015 film)|The Descendants]]'' series.\n\nDuring the [[Memorial Day]] holiday weekend of 2016, Disney Channel began to air many of the older DCOMs in a marathon format. The marathon began in celebration of its 100th Disney Channel Original Movie, ''[[Adventures in Babysitting (2016 film)|Adventures in Babysitting]]''. Disney Channel broadcast all of the 99 Disney Channel Original Movies that came before it, beginning with the 51 most popular films airing over the four-day weekend, beginning May 27, 2016.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ew.com/article/2016/04/20/disney-channel-memorial-day-schedule-dcom |last=Kickham |first=Dylan |title=Disney Channel airing DCOM Memorial Day mega-marathon: See the schedule |work=[[Entertainment Weekly]] |date=April 20, 2016 |access-date=2017-03-18}}</ref> The network continued to screen the rest of its original movies throughout the month of June 2016, before the June 24 premiere of the 100th Disney Channel Original Film.<ref name=\"BuzzFeed\" />\n\n==Disney Channel Premiere Films==\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders sortable\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | Year\n! scope=\"col\" | Film\n! scope=\"col\" data-sort-type=\"date\" | Premiere date\n! scope=\"col\" class=\"unsortable\" | {{Abbr|Ref(s)|References}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"text-align:center;\" rowspan=\"2\"| 1983\n|''[[Tiger Town]]''\n| October 9, 1983\n| <ref>{{cite news|title=A Salute to Disney Channel: Disney Channel time line|url=http://kidscreen.com/1998/04/01/21442-19980401/|accessdate=2017-03-16|work=Kidscreen|publisher=Brunico Communications Ltd.|date=April 1, 1998}}</ref> \n|-\n|''Just Like Mr. Sunny''\n| December 4, 1983\n| \n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"text-align:center;\" rowspan=\"2\"| 1984\n|''[[Gone Are the Dayes]]''\n| May 6, 1984\n| \n|-\n|''Love Leads the Way''\n| October 7, 1984\n| \n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"text-align:center;\" rowspan=\"4\"| 1985\n|''[[Lots of Luck]]''\n| February 3, 1985\n| \n|-\n|''The Undergrads''\n| May 5, 1985\n| \n|-\n|''The Caldercott Story''\n| August 2, 1985\n| \n|-\n|''[[The Blue Yonder]]''\n| November 17, 1985\n| \n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"text-align:center;\" rowspan=\"5\"| 1986\n|''Help Wanted: Kids''\n| February 2, 1986\n| \n|-\n|''[[Mr. Boogedy]]''\n| April 20, 1986\n| \n|-\n|''[[The Parent Trap II]]''\n| July 26, 1986\n| \n|-\n|''[[Spot Marks the X]]''\n| October 18, 1986\n| \n|-\n|''Down the Long Hills''\n| November 15, 1986\n| \n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"text-align:center;\" rowspan=\"4\"| 1987\n|''Strange Companions''\n| February 28, 1987\n| \n|-\n|''[[Anne of Green Gables: The Sequel|Anne of Avonlea: The Continuing Story of Anne of Green Gables]]''\n| May 19, 1987\n| \n|-\n|''[[Not Quite Human (film)|Not Quite Human]]''\n| June 19, 1987\n| \n|-\n|''The Christmas Visitor''\n| December 5, 1987\n| \n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"text-align:center;\" rowspan=\"7\"| 1988\n|''Rock N Roll Mom''\n| February 7, 1988\n| \n|-\n|''Save the Dog''\n| March 19, 1988\n| \n|-\n|''[[Night Train to Kathmandu]]''\n| June 5, 1988\n| \n|-\n|''[[Ollie Hopnoodle's Haven of Bliss]]''\n| August 6, 1988\n| \n|-\n|''A Friendship in Vienna''\n| August 27, 1988\n| \n|-\n|''Good Old Boy''\n| November 11, 1988\n| \n|-\n|''Goodbye, Miss 4th of July''\n| December 3, 1988\n| \n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"text-align:center;\" rowspan=\"3\"| 1989\n| ''[[Parent Trap III]]''\n| April 9, 1989\n| \n|-\n|''[[Not Quite Human II]]''\n| September 23, 1989\n| \n|-\n|''[[Parent Trap: Hawaiian Honeymoon]]''\n| November 19, 1989\n| \n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"text-align:center;\" rowspan=\"6\"| 1990\n|''[[Lantern Hill (film)|Lantern Hill]]''\n| January 27, 1990\n| \n|-\n| ''Chips, the War Dog''\n| March 24, 1990\n| \n|-\n|''[[Mother Goose Rock 'n' Rhyme]]''\n| May 19, 1990\n| \n|-\n|''[[Back Home (film)|Back Home]]''\n| June 7, 1990\n| \n|-\n|''[[The Little Kidnappers (1990 film)|The Little Kidnappers]]''\n| August 17, 1990\n| \n|-\n|''[[Back to Hannibal: The Return of Tom Sawyer and Huckleberry Finn]]''\n| October 21, 1990\n| \n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"text-align:center;\" rowspan=\"3\"| 1991\n|''Bejewelled''\n| January 20, 1991\n| \n|-\n|''[[Perfect Harmony (film)|Perfect Harmony]]''\n| March 31, 1991\n| \n|-\n|''Mark Twain and Me''\n| November 22, 1991\n| \n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"text-align:center;\" | 1992\n| ''[[Still Not Quite Human]]''\n| May 31, 1992\n| \n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"text-align:center;\" rowspan=\"4\"| 1993\n|''[[The Ernest Green Story]]''\n| January 17, 1993\n| \n|-\n|''Spies''\n| March 7, 1993\n| <ref>''The Disney Channel Magazine'', Vol. 11, no. 2, February/March 1993: pp. 38, 42.</ref>\n|-\n|''[[Heidi (miniseries)|Heidi]]''\n| July 18, 1993\n| \n|-\n|''[[Airborne (1993 film)|Airborne]]''\n| September 17, 1993\n| \n|-\n<!-- DO ''not'' ADD \"Hocus Pocus (1993 film)\" TO THIS LIST. It was released theatrically by Walt Disney Pictures, it was ''not'' a Disney Channel Original Movie! -->\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"text-align:center;\" rowspan=\"2\"| 1994\n|''On Promised Land''\n| April 17, 1994\n| \n|-\n|''[[The Whipping Boy]]''\n| July 31, 1994\n| \n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"text-align:center;\" rowspan=\"3\"| 1995\n|''[[The Old Curiosity Shop]]''\n| March 19, 1995\n| \n|-\n|''[[Escape to Witch Mountain (1995 film)|Escape to Witch Mountain]]''\n| April 29, 1995\n| \n|-\n|''[[The Four Diamonds]]''\n| August 12, 1995\n| \n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"text-align:center;\" rowspan=\"4\"| 1996\n|''[[The Little Riders]]''\n| March 24, 1996\n| \n|-\n|''[[Nightjohn]]''\n| June 1, 1996\n| \n|-\n|''[[Susie Q (film)|Susie Q]]''\n| mid-1996   <!-- Note: Date sorting for this entry is broken - without an exact premiere date (which is not known), it will remain broken... \u2013 actually premiered first on Germany's Super RTL, but still indicate as a Disney Channel Premiere Films at MTV News --> \n|<ref>{{c